ot more fresh than when the other sequels started to come out (not that that makes those games any worse). Resident Evil was great, but 2 took it to a whole new level. You weren't trapped in a mansion anymore, you're in a city of the undead with nowhere to run. The other games were great too, but there are so many memorable moments in this game that it beats them all out.<br><br>Deus Ex- This is definitely one of the best FPS games ever made in my opinion. This is the first one I've played that had a really strong storyline, proving this genre wasn't just mindless fun. The RPG elements definitely added a lot to the gameplay, and the character interaction and storyline really made you want to keep playing. Completing a solid mission with real consequences and effects is so much more satisfying than just beating a level and moving on. The different outcomes and affects depending on your actions also made this game great.<br><br>Metal Gear Solid 1- Well, 2 would have been better, but the story for that one was... terrible. It was a very fun game, but the storyline of MGS is a big part of the game, and if it's bad, it taints the experience, and that's why it's not one of my favorites. Luckily, that wasn't a problem with part 1. The gameplay, the story, the graphics (at the time) were all great. It did have pretty good voice acting, but it definitely wasn't the best in any game as most people claim. Still, it's better than most, and the gameplay and everything else supports it.<br><br>Chrono Trigger/Final Fantasy 7- Definitely my two favorite RPG's. I'm not a huge fan of the genre, but these two were certainlly great. The characters were all varied and memorable. The stories were involving and interesting, and in the case of Chrono Trigger had multiple outcomes. I know I listed more than 4, but these games deserved mention. <p><table width=100% border=0><tr><td>Thomas Bonvillain<br><img src=http://www.undeadart.com/temp/banner/banner.gif><a href=http://www